, Dutch, and North German: from early Middle English <i>penning</i>, Low German <i>penning</i>, Middle Dutch <i>penninc</i> ‘penny’ (see   Penny  ), a topographic name (from a field name) or a nickname referring to tax dues of a penny.","South German: from the short form, <i>Panno</i>, of an ancient Germanic personal name derived from a word meaning ‘ban, order, command’.","English: from a Middle English personal name <i>Pening</i>, <i>Pining</i>, presumably representing an unrecorded Old English name, a pet form perhaps of <i>Penda</i> or of names like <i>Pendhere</i> and <i>Pendwulf</i>."]},{"name":"Pinyan","meanings":["English: variant of   Pinion  ."]}]},{"name":"Ifor","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional name of uncertain derivation; sometimes Anglicized as   Ivor  , but there is no connection in origin between the two names."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Ifor ap Einion was born in 1170, in Senghenydd, Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom, his father, Einion ap Llywarch, was 6 and his mother, Tangwystl verch Rhys, was 16. He had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with Lleucu Ferch Madog."},"et":{"1170–":"1170–Surnud","1170–Male":"1170–Surnud","1195–1206":"1195–1206","–Male":"Surnud","1195–Female":"1195–Surnud","1195–Male":"1195–Surnud","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","1225–Male":"1225–Surnud","1230–Male":"1230–Surnud","1233–Female":"1233–Surnud","1238–Male":"1238–Surnud","0903–Male":"0903–Surnud","1226–Female":"1226–Surnud","1165–1197":"1165–1197","1155–Female":"1155–Surnud","1165":"1165","1197":"1197","1230":"1230","1195":"1195","1170":"1170","ABT    1226":"umbes 1226","1206":"1206","1238":"1238","1226":"1226","1225":"1225","1233":"1233","1200":"1200","about 1238":"umbes 1238","1155":"1155","0903":"0903","Radnorshire, Wales":"Radnorshire, Wales, United Kingdom","of,,Cardiganshire,Wales":"Cardiganshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Senghennydd cantref, Glamorganshire, Wales":"